WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.700
Thank you. I'm going to talk a little bit about transplant and it's appropriate. We are on the end. We had been on the end for a long time. End of the patients, end of the journey, end of everything. Only what I would say, I was recently in China. We in Baylor had CD7 CAR-T and I think they did 10 patients. We were so excited.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:28.440
In China, at the same time, they did 450 CD7 CAR-T and conclusion was you still need a transplant.

00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:30.980
So I think until we retire, we have enough business.

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:39.340
So let me give you a little bit about PTCI because whatever you do with the transplant, you'll be hitting some of these issues.

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:45.300
So PTCI, a relatively new kid in the block since early 2000.

00:00:45.900 --> 00:00:48.720
There have been so many different studies very nicely outlined.

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:50.620
I'll give a little bit more perspective.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:54.240
And probably two most important, two recent New England Journal of Medicine,

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:57.700
which really puts it in a lot of perspective as a standard of care.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:03.360
Just to put it a quick summary, it is universal GVHD prophylaxis.

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:09.760
According to NNDP, approximately 70 to 80% of entire transplants are being done with PTCI.

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:16.520
It works across the HLA donor success, the graft sources, across conditioning regimens.

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:20.200
A few points to understand, relapse is not

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:22.000
increased with PTCI.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.600
It is exactly the same, if not even a little bit better than no increase of PTLD.

00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:33.580
There are new strategies that you can build up this transplant and stop immunosuppression early, because I think we are all learning.

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:38.500
The next setup is how do we bring something as X in the context of the transplant?

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:42.040
And it's most importantly, the transplants are being done around the world.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:49.160
So same thing, what we talk about, the transplants are currently routinely done in entire, entire China.

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:49.960
It is done in the.

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:52.420
All far east, Latin America.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:54.880
So this is something which works around the world.

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:59.860
Other things worth considering is that you have multiple donors to choose.

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:02.600
And we discuss, I'm not going to get into discussion.

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.320
So at this moment, every patient should have a donor.

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:11.800
There are variability of the donors depending on your center's preferences and your urgency for the patients.

00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:19.420
Just few numbers to highlight for the haploidentical, more than 95% of entire transplants are done with PTCI.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:21.780
These are all data on the mods.

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:31.780
I currently is around 70% of entire mods are done by repeat PTCI mismatch mods, probably around 90% are also being done with PTCI.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:37.360
So it's becoming really a common prophylaxis that a majority of your patients might encounter.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:42.040
So what are the current strategies for the PTCI further optimization?

00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:48.580
The bigger question is what we just briefly discussed is the optimal dose of 50 times to the right dose.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:49.480
And I'm going to touch.

00:02:49.480 --> 00:03:01.840
A little bit about it, how we can address some of the toxicities and CRS with PTCI and bone and peripheral blood specifically, if you are hitting donor over 70 can be an issue.

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:08.260
It is not the same as a CAR-T, but there are issues with some CRS in all the patients.

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:19.240
If you are using a peripheral blood, other issue is most importantly, how we can combine PTCI with new agents, because we are also getting excited about some of the

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:21.760
the new agents which are coming through the portfolios.

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:32.140
So a few things, PTCI 100 versus 80, this was very old question specifically in the China because of LDH enzyme, which is started with PTCI.

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:36.820
There was a question, does this impact survival in the Asian population?

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:43.600
And based on this retrospective data and clinical trials from the from the Japanese group, there could be no difference.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:49.000
So if you really want to cut and cut a little bit, which is for the TIE2, it seems there is very solid data.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.080
The data from Japan, there is no major difference in outcome.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:59.020
This is the data from combined study from French and Italian group against showing the dose.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:02.320
If you want to cut 40 BID, there are no randomized trials.

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:04.260
It seems to be the survival is the same.

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:10.420
You might have actually a little bit less VK virus, but are the old centers comfortable?

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:12.340
And which patient do you want to cut?

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:14.140
It is up to the centers.

00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:18.520
There is no real randomized studies to decide what is the better.

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:24.340
But this is the kind of where there is a solid retrospective institution data.

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:27.460
So the question is, can you even cut it further?

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:30.580
This is one of the hottest questions in the transplant field.

00:04:30.580 --> 00:04:35.500
There are a few studies trying to cut PTCI going over up to the dose of 25.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:41.280
You said the data from and from NCI Chris can actually a few differences.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:48.520
This is this was done mostly with bone marrow graft and in context of serolimus prophylaxis, serolimus

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:50.920
works sometimes better than the TAC limus.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:52.180
So you really need to be attuned.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:53.440
What are you doing?

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:56.080
And this had been tested mostly in the younger patients.

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:01.720
Results looked pretty reasonable and pretty good for 25 based on the published data.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:05.980
There is ongoing trials between between NCI and UPenn.

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:09.700
There will be paper coming soon with those of 25 PTCI.

00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:12.520
So there will be a little bit more data for you who are interested.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:17.080
It appears there might be a little bit more chronic GVHD, but this is something what we need to learn.

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:25.660
Early outcomes, what NCI group had reported, pretty good incidence of grade two and grade three and four GVHD.

00:05:25.660 --> 00:05:31.180
So if you have a patient who really needs it, this is something to try.

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:36.340
But again, there are no real data to improve this in the peripheral blood.

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:40.000
And the majority of our grafts these days are in the peripheral blood.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:48.040
Other interesting story, because as we are pushing the transplant beyond age 70 to the late 70s, little CRS.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:56.500
Specifically, when you give a graft, you have these four days without immunosuppression can have prominent effects on all the patients.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:06:03.800
And there was a very interesting study done by a group of Washu who basically integrated JAK inhibitor in context of PTCI,

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:10.840
which opens an entire new way where we might be going by adding JAK inhibitors.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:17.800
They had very, very good data on this prevention, CRS, outcomes were pretty good.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:21.820
But the only thing that was really interesting was that this drug was pulled out of the market because this was etacitinib.

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:25.120
It was pulled out because of inefficacy in other setting.

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:29.200
People are now trying to get the Ruxolitinib, something to be looking into it.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:36.040
But I think we'll be seeing more and more of these agents coming in in the context of a post-graft immunosuppression.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:43.720
Which leaves me now that something for you all to watch for, and there will be BMT CTN trials, there will be other trials and some of your institution.

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:47.560
The biggest question is currently how do we move haploid related,

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:58.900
unrelated to PTCI with other partners and JAK inhibitor is something which is happening earlier this on how we can bring this surgeon and why we should be doing this.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:06.820
Because as we are hearing for last few days for our leukemia colleagues, there is a huge, huge interest to continue this maintenance post-transplant.

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:17.320
And the sooner we can have shortened immunosuppression, stop it earlier so we can give this additional agency, some of what we'll be doing, it probably will be focus of all of

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:19.540
our efforts in the next 10 years.

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:29.360
So I really don't have a right answer what is the partner X, very likely JAK inhibitor will be coming and it will be something we'll be having the two different roles,

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:32.440
prevention of CRS and prevention of GVHD.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:36.460
And this is certainly where we are doing, I think 225, this is old slide.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:43.940
We are all improved, we can transplant everybody, but best what we can do is the 40, 50% five-year survival.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:47.080
So last 20 years, we can deliver this now to everybody.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:51.100
But in the need, but how do we go to the higher numbers?

00:07:51.100 --> 00:08:02.520
This is where we need to do a learn and PTSI, head expanded access, but we think it's also the platform to move this curve to the higher numbers and give better outcomes to our patients.

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:03.820
Thank you very much.
